GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
S 2
SENATE BILL 587
Second Edition Engrossed 5/7/25
Short Title: Clarify Nonconforming Uses. (Public)
Sponsors: Senators Lazzara and Sawrey (Primary Sponsors).
Referred to: Rules and Operations of the Senate
March 26, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO CLARIFY NONCONFORMITIES IN LAND DEVELOPMENT
3 REGULATIONS.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. G.S. 160D-102 is amended by adding a new subdivision to read:
6 "(23m) Nonconformity. – Any of the following that was lawfully operated,
7 established, or commenced in accordance with applicable development
8 regulations in effect at the time the nonconformity became nonconforming so
9 long as the nonconformity is not extended, expanded, enlarged, increased, or
10 intensified:
11 a. A lot, parcel, or tract of land that fails to meet all current development
12 regulation requirements.
13 b. A structure that no longer complies with all current development
14 regulation requirements applicable to that structure.
15 c. The use of a property for a purpose or activity, or in a manner, made
16 unlawful by a current development regulation.
17 d. Any dwelling, accessory building, accessory structure, outdoor
18 lighting, fence, wall, sign, off-street parking, vehicular surface area, or
19 private access point."
20 SECTION 2. Article 1 of Chapter 160D of the General Statutes is amended by
21 adding a new section to read:
22 "§ 160D-108.2. Nonconformities.
23 (a) Amendments in land development regulations are not applicable or enforceable
24 without the written consent of the owner with regard to a nonconformity. All of the following
25 shall apply to vested rights in a nonconformity established under this section:
26 (1) The establishment of a vested right under this section does not preclude
27 vesting under one or more other provisions of law or vesting by application of
28 common law principles.
29 (2) A vested right, once established as provided for in this section or by common
30 law, precludes any action by a local government that would change, alter,
31 impair, prevent, diminish, or otherwise delay the development or use of the
32 property allowed by applicable development regulations, except where a
33 change in State or federal law mandating local government enforcement
34 occurs after the nonconformity was established that has a fundamental and
35 retroactive effect on the development or use.
36 (3) G.S. 160D-108(h) shall apply to the claiming of nonconformities.
*S587-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (4) Unless otherwise specified by this section or another statute, a nonconformity
2 may continue until intentionally and voluntarily discontinued.
3 (b) The statutory vesting period granted by this section for a nonconformity expires if the
4 nonconformity is intentionally and voluntarily discontinued for a period of not less than 24
5 consecutive months. The 24-month discontinuance period shall be automatically tolled during
6 any of the following events:
7 (1) The pendency of any board of adjustment proceeding or civil action in a State
8 or federal court regarding the validity of the use of the property or the
9 existence of the statutory vesting period granted by this section.
10 (2) The pendency of any litigation involving use of the property that is the subject
11 of the vesting.
12 (3) The duration of any emergency declaration issued under G.S. 166A-19.20 or
13 G.S. 166A-19.22 for which the defined emergency area includes the property,
14 in whole or in part.
15 (c) Reconstruction, re-establishment, repair, and maintenance of a nonconformity shall
16 be allowed by right provided the nonconforming is not extended, expanded, enlarged, increased,
17 or intensified by the reconstruction, re-establishment, repair, or maintenance.
18 (d) This section shall not apply to G.S. 160D-912 and G.S. 160D-912.1."
19 SECTION 3. G.S. 160D-108 reads as rewritten:
20 "§ 160D-108. Permit choice and vested rights.
21 …
22 (d) Duration of Vesting. – Upon issuance of a development permit, the statutory vesting
23 granted by subsection (c) of this section for a development project is effective upon filing of the
24 application in accordance with G.S. 143-755, for so long as the permit remains valid pursuant to
25 law. Unless otherwise specified by this section or other statute, local development permits expire
26 one year after issuance unless work authorized by the permit has substantially commenced. A
27 local land development regulation may provide for a longer permit expiration period. For the
28 purposes of this section, a permit is issued either in the ordinary course of business of the
29 applicable governmental agency or by the applicable governmental agency as a court directive.
30 Except where a longer vesting period is provided by statute or land development regulation,
31 the statutory vesting granted by this section, once established, expires for an uncompleted
32 development project if development work is intentionally and voluntarily discontinued for a
33 period of not less than 24 consecutive months, and the statutory vesting period granted by this
34 section for a nonconforming use of property expires if the use is intentionally and voluntarily
35 discontinued for a period of not less than 24 consecutive months. The 24-month discontinuance
36 period is automatically tolled during any of the following:
37 (1) the The pendency of any board of adjustment proceeding or civil action in a
38 State or federal trial or appellate court regarding the validity of a development
39 permit, the use of the property, or the existence of the statutory vesting period
40 granted by this section.
41 (2) The 24-month discontinuance period is also tolled during the pendency of any
42 litigation involving the development project or property that is the subject of
43 the vesting.
44 (3) The duration of any emergency declaration issued under G.S. 166A-19.20 or
45 G.S. 166A-19.22 for which the defined emergency area includes the property,
46 in whole or in part.
47 …
48 (h) Process to Claim Vested Right. – A person claiming a statutory or common law vested
49 right may submit information to substantiate that claim to the zoning administrator or other
50 officer designated by a land development regulation, who shall make an initial determination as
51 to the existence of the vested right. The decision of the zoning administrator or officer may be
